pull_request.body:
Bumps [actions/download-artifact](https://github.com/actions/download-artifact) from 4.3.0 to 5.0.0.
Release notes

Sourced from actions/download-artifact's releases.

v5.0.0

What's Changed

  • Update README.md by @‚Äãnebuk89 in actions/download-artifact#407
  • BREAKING fix: inconsistent path behavior for single artifact downloads by ID by @‚ÄãGrantBirki in actions/download-artifact#416

v5.0.0

üö® Breaking Change

This release fixes an inconsistency in path behavior for single artifact downloads by ID. If you're downloading single artifacts by ID, the output path may change.

What Changed

Previously, single artifact downloads behaved differently depending on how you specified the artifact:

  • By name: name: my-artifact ‚Üí extracted to path/ (direct)
  • By ID: artifact-ids: 12345 ‚Üí extracted to path/my-artifact/ (nested)

Now both methods are consistent:

  • By name: name: my-artifact ‚Üí extracted to path/ (unchanged)
  • By ID: artifact-ids: 12345 ‚Üí extracted to path/ (fixed - now direct)

Migration Guide

‚úÖ No Action Needed If:
  • You download artifacts by name
  • You download multiple artifacts by ID
  • You already use merge-multiple: true as a workaround
‚ö†Ô∏è Action Required If:

You download single artifacts by ID and your workflows expect the nested directory structure.

Before v5 (nested structure):

- uses: actions/download-artifact@v4
  with:
    artifact-ids: 12345
    path: dist
# Files were in: dist/my-artifact/

Where my-artifact is the name of the artifact you previously uploaded

To maintain old behavior (if needed):

pull_request.body:
## Summary
- Fixes static file serving issue where user CSS files in `/static/css/` were returning 404
- Removes conflicting `/static/css/{filename}` route that was intercepting requests
- Adds `static_path` parameter to `StarHTML` constructor for better usability

## Problem
StarHTML had a built-in route `/static/css/{filename}` that intercepted all requests to `/static/css/*` before the general static file serving route could handle them. This route was looking for CSS files in StarHTML's package directory (which doesn't exist), causing user files to return 404.

## Solution  
Removed the conflicting route. Now user files in `/static/css/` are correctly served by the general static file route.

‚úÖ All existing tests pass

pull_request.title: fix: handle locals() calls in wrapped modules by static analysis
pull_request.body:
## Summary

This PR fixes bundling of modules that use `locals()` to dynamically access imported symbols, a pattern used by libraries like httpx to set `__module__` attributes.

## Changes

- **Static analysis for `locals()` calls**: When a module-level `locals()` call is detected, it's replaced with a statically determined dictionary containing all module-level symbols
- **`__all__` reference detection**: Added detection for when `__all__` variable is referenced elsewhere in the module (e.g., in loops), ensuring it's preserved when needed
- **AST builder enhancement**: Added `dict()` and `dict_item()` helper functions to the ast_builder for cleaner dictionary construction
- **Test fixture**: Added test case based on httpx's pattern of using `locals()` to access imported symbols

## Problem & Solution

The issue occurred when bundling modules that use this pattern:
```python
from ._internal import MyClass, my_func
__all__ = ["MyClass", "my_func"]
__locals = locals()  # Capture module-level locals
for __name in __all__:
    setattr(__locals[__name], "__module__", "mypkg")
```

In the bundled wrapper function, `locals()` returns function-local variables, not the imported symbols which are now global. The solution uses static analysis to determine what `locals()` would return at module level and replaces it with a dictionary literal containing the correct symbols.

## Test Results

- ‚úÖ All existing tests pass
- ‚úÖ New test fixture for the httpx pattern works correctly
- ‚úÖ Clippy validation passes (only unused `dict_item` warning, kept for future use)
